{"id":"1212.2277","submitter":"Gustavo R. Gonzalez-Martin","authors":"Gustavo R. Gonzalez-Martin","title":"Geometric gravitational origin of neutrino oscillations and mass-energy","comments":"20 pages, 1 figure. Energy numerical value in eq. (12) was revised.\n  Relation to solar neutrinos was clarified. Appendix C is fully revised.\n  Equations renumbered. Revisions were made to provide a clearer theoretical\n  derivation of the neutrino motion. Minor corrections were made. Results\n  remain the same","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A mass-energy scale for neutrinos was calculated from the null cone curvature\nusing geometric concepts. The scale is variable depending on the gravitational\npotential and the trajectory inclination with respect to the field direction.\nThe proposed neutrino covariant equation provides the adequate curvature. The\nmass-energy at the Earth surface varies from a horizontal value 0.402 eV to a\nvertical value 0.569 eV. Earth spinor waves with winding numbers n show squared\nenergy differences within ranges from 2.05 x 10*(-3) to 4.10 x 10*(-3) eV*2 for\nn=0,1 neutrinos and from 3.89 x 10*(-5) to 7.79 x 10*(-5) eV*2 for n=1,2\nneutrinos. These waves interfere and the different phase velocities produce\nneutrino-like oscillations. The experimental results for atmospheric and solar\nneutrino oscillation mass parameters respectivelly fall within these\ntheoretical ranges. Neutrinos in outer space, where interactions may be\nneglected, appear as particles travelling with zero mass on null geodesics.\nThese gravitational curvature energies are consistent with neutrino\noscillations, zero neutrino rest masses and Einstein's General Relativity and\nenergy mass equivalence principle. When analyzing or averaging experimental\nneutrino mass-energy results of different experiments on the Earth it is of\ninterest to consider the possible influence of the trajectory inclination\nangle.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Dec 2012 14:35:40 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 21 Dec 2012 12:14:52 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 31 Oct 2013 16:52:35 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 21 May 2014 12:43:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-05-22"}
